## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Cannot forcibly kill threads |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Removed** | No equivalent needed |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never thrown** | Dead code path |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can interrupt `finally` blocks, leave locks held, and cause resource leaks.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative cancellation timeout.
    /// The delegate must observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> for timely exit.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original Thread.Join(timeout) did.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Task.Wait() already unwraps faulted tasks as AggregateException,
        // preserving the original behavior.
        return task.Result;
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async overload — preferred in new code.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage — Before vs After

```csharp
// ── .NET Framework (old) ──
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowComputation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ── .NET 8 (new) ──
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowComputation(ct),   // pass token into the work
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ── .NET 8 async (preferred) ──
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct => await SlowComputationAsync(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### Critical Pitfall: Cooperative Cancellation

The old code **forcibly killed** the thread. The new model is **cooperative** — work must check the token:

```csharp
// ✅ Correct — respects cancellation
int SlowComputation(CancellationToken ct)
{
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // exit point
        Process(item);
    }
    return total;
}

// ❌ Broken — ignores the token, runs forever on timeout
int SlowComputation(CancellationToken ct)
{
    Thread.Sleep(60_000);  // never checks ct
    return 42;
}
```

### Escape Hatch: Uncooperative Code You Can't Modify

If you call third-party code that doesn't accept a `CancellationToken`, you can **abandon** it (let it finish on a background thread) rather than block your caller:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeoutUncooperative<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    var task = Task.Run(work);

    if (task.Wait(timeout))
        return task.Result;

    // Task keeps running but we stop waiting — no way to force-kill it.
    // Log the abandoned task so it doesn't silently leak.
    _ = task.ContinueWith(t =>
        Console.Error.WriteLine($"Abandoned task faulted: {t.Exception}"),
        TaskContinuationOptions.OnlyOnFaulted);

    throw new TimeoutException(
        $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout (task abandoned)");
}
```

> ⚠️ This **leaks the background work** — it keeps running. Use only as a last resort for code you can't modify.

### Summary

| Concern | Action |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort` / `ResetAbort` | Replace with `CancellationTokenSource` |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch | Remove — never thrown in .NET 8 |
| Signature change | Add `CancellationToken` parameter to `Func<T>` |
| Callers | Update all call sites to pass and observe the token |
| Third-party code | Use the abandon pattern with `Task.Wait(timeout)` |
| New code | Prefer the `async` overload with `WaitAsync` |
